{
  format: 1
  name: migration-program-reads-old-top-level-view
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#evolution", "§20.1", "#views", "§7", "#loading", "§9.4"]
  note: '''
    §20.1: "`$old` is the complete read-only state under the delta's source
    model … it MAY read any `$old` view." A declared top-level `$view` (§7) is
    the canonical view, so a delta MUST be able to read AND project it.

    The 1.0.0 model declares `big` as `.items[:i | i.qty > 5] { id, qty }`. The
    2.0.0 delta `.kept = $old.big { id, qty }` reads that source view and
    projects its rows. Seed: i1 (qty 5) is excluded by the view filter, i2
    (qty 7) and i3 (qty 9) are kept — so `kept` holds exactly i2 and i3, proving
    the delta reads the FILTERED, PROJECTED view rows (not the raw `items`).

    Regression: the model's `ViewDecl.row` is an empty placeholder for an
    ordinary `$view`, so a migration binding `$old` as a plain row typed
    `$old.big` with no fields and rejected `$old.big { id, qty }` as an unknown
    name — even though the view VALUE was materialized. The `$old` type now
    carries each source view's compiled projected row.
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.mig.oldview@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      items: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        qty: "int"
      }
      big: { $view: ".items[:i | i.qty > 5] { id, qty }" }
      $public: {
        items: { $view: ".items { id, qty }" }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      items: {
        i1: { qty: "5" }
        i2: { qty: "7" }
        i3: { qty: "9" }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { host_load: {
        package: {
          $liasse: 1
          $app: "t.mig.oldview@2.0.0"
          $model: {
            kept: {
              $key: "id"
              id: "text"
              qty: "int"
            }
            $migrations: {
              "1.0.0": [
                ".kept = $old.big { id, qty }"
              ]
            }
            $public: {
              kept: { $view: ".kept { id, qty, $sort: [id] }" }
            }
          }
        }
      }
      expect: { outcome: ok, result: committed } }
    { watch: "public.kept", id: "wk",
      expect_init: { value: [
        { id: "i2", qty: "7" }
        { id: "i3", qty: "9" }
      ] } }
  ]
}
